Kinds of errors:
\begin{itemize}
\item \dred{Syntax error.}  Python cannot understand your program, and refuses to execute it.
\item \dred{Runtime error.}  When executing your program (\dred{at runtime}), your program suddenly terminates with an error message.
\item \dred{Semantic error.}  Your program runs without error messages, but does not do what it is supposed to do.
\end{itemize}

\begin{V}
\dred@def$ print_message\dred@():$
  print "CS101 is fantastic!"
  print "Programming is fun!"
\end{V}

You can call a function inside another function:

\begin{V}
def repeat_message():
  print_message()
  print_message()
\end{V}

\begin{V}
def print_message():
  print "CS101 is fantastic!"
  print "Programming is so much fun!"

def repeat_message():
  print_message()
  print_message()

repeat_message()
\end{V}

\begin{V} # create a robot with one beeper hubo = Robot(beepers = 1)
# move one step forward hubo.move()
# turn left 90 degrees hubo.turn_left() \end{V}

\begin{V}
def turn_right():
  hubo.turn_left()
  hubo.turn_left()
  hubo.turn_left()
\end{V}

\begin{V}
def turn_around():
  hubo.turn_left()
  hubo.turn_left()
\end{V}

\begin{V}
def climb_up_four_stairs():
  # how?
\end{V}

\begin{V}
def climb_up_four_stairs():
  climb_up_one_stair()
  climb_up_one_stair()
  climb_up_one_stair()
  climb_up_one_stair()
\end{V}

\begin{V}
def climb_up_one_stair():
  hubo.turn_left()
  hubo.move()
  turn_right()
  hubo.move()
  hubo.move()
\end{V}

To repeat the same instruction 4 times:

\begin{V}
\dred@for$ i \dred@in$ range(4)\dred@:$
  print "CS101 is fantastic!"
\end{V}

What is the difference:

\begin{V}
for i in range(4):
  print "CS101 is great!"
  print "I love programming!"
\end{V}

and 

\begin{V}
for i in range(4):
  print "CS101 is great!"
print "I love programming!"
\end{V}

\begin{V}
def climb_up_four_stairs():
  climb_up_one_stair()
  climb_up_one_stair()
  climb_up_one_stair()
  climb_up_one_stair()
\end{V}

We should avoid writing the same code repeatedly.  A |for|-loop allows us to write this more elegantly:

\begin{V}
def climb_up_four_stairs():
  for i in range(4):
    climb_up_one_stair()
\end{V}
